'''[[裙子|裙子]]'''在西方時尚文化當道的現代社會，多被當成是[[女性|女性]]的典型[[服裝|服裝]]，然而在非西方文化及歐洲歷史的不同時期，[[男性|男性]]的主要服裝其實包括裙裝及類似長裙的[[長袍|袍子]]，例如聖職人員穿著的[[法衣_(基督教)|法衣]]和蘇格蘭男性穿著的[[蘇格蘭裙|短裙]]。熱帶地區男性穿著罩袍，至今仍是日常普遍的傳統服裝。

現今西方社會曾有人嘗試提倡男性穿裙，並企圖消除這種[[性別角色|性別角色]]的差異；但是，裙子自16世紀以來，一直被當成是女性的服裝，男性已經拋棄穿裙的習俗，因此這項倡議雖然取得有限的成功<ref>"...[despite] the best efforts of designers like Jean Paul Gaultier and others, the men's skirt has failed to gain popularity (though the kilt appears appropriate wear for men on certain special occasions)." Fiona Margaret Wilson (2003), ''Organizational Behaviour and Gender.'' Ashgate Publishing, Ltd. {{ISBN|0-7546-0900-6}}, p. 199.</ref>，卻也遭遇巨大的文化阻力<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/Archive/Article/0,4273,4342129,00.html The Guardian], January 2002</ref>。

== 西方文化 ==
{{TransH}}
=== 古代 ===
Skirts have been worn since prehistoric times. They were the standard dressing for men and women in all ancient cultures in the [[近東|Near East]] and [[埃及|Egypt]].

The Kingdom of [[苏美尔|Sumer]] in [[美索不达米亚|Mesopotamia]] recorded two categories of clothing. The ritual attire for men was a fur skirt tied to a belt called {{tsl|en|Kaunakes||Kaunakes}}. The term kaunakes, which originally referred to a sheep's fleece, was later applied to the garment itself. The animal pelts originally used were replaced by kaunakes cloth, a textile that imitated fleecy sheep skin.<ref>Boucher, Francois (1987): 20,000 Years of Fashion: The History of Costume and Personal Adornment. New York: Harry N. Abrams</ref> Kaunakes cloth also served as a symbol in religious iconography, as the fleecy cloak of [[施洗約翰|St. John the Baptist]].<ref>The Bible: Genesis 12:4–5</ref><ref>Roberts, J.M. (1998): The Illustrated History of the World. Time-Life Books. Volume 1. p. 84</ref>

Depictions of kings and their attendants from the {{tsl|en|Old Assyrian Empire||Old Assyrian Empire}} and [[巴比倫尼亞|Babylonia]] on monuments like the Black Obelisk of Salmanazar show men wearing fringed cloths wrapped around their sleeved tunics.<ref>Rief Anawalt, Patricia (2007): The Worldwide History of Dress. London: Thames & Hudson. p. 22</ref>

[[古埃及|Ancient Egypt]]ian garments were mainly made of white linen.<ref>Barber, Elisabeth J.W. (1991): Prehistoric Textiles: The Development of Cloth in the Neolithic and Bronze Ages with Special Reference to the Aegean. Princeton: Princeton University Press. p. 12.</ref> The exclusive use of draped linen garments, and the wearing of similar styles by men and women, remained almost unaltered as the main features of Ancient Egyptian costume. From about 2130 BC during the [[古王國時期|Old Kingdom of Egypt]], men also wore wrap around skirts (kilts) known as the {{tsl|en|shendyt||shendyt}}, They were made of a rectangular piece of cloth wrapped around the lower body and tied in front. By the [[中王國時期|Middle Kingdom of Egypt]] there was a fashion for longer kilts, almost like skirts, reaching from the waist to ankles, sometimes hanging from the armpits. During the [[新王國時期|New Kingdom of Egypt]], kilts with a pleated triangular section became fashionable for men.<ref>Rief Anawalt, Patricia (2007): The Worldwide History of Dress. London: Thames & Hudson. p. 25</ref> Beneath was worn a triangular {{tsl|en|loincloth||loincloth}}, or shente,{{which lang|date=May 2021}} whose ends were fastened with cord ties.<ref>Rief Anawalt, Patricia (2007): The Worldwide History of Dress. London: Thames & Hudson. p. 24</ref>

In [[古希腊|Ancient Greece]] the simple, sleeved T-shaped tunics were constructed of three seamed tubes of cloth, a style that originated in the Semitic Near East, along with the [[闪米特语族|Semitic]]-based word khiton, also referred to as a {{tsl|en|Chiton (costume)||chiton}}.<ref>Rief Anawalt, Patricia (2007): The Worldwide History of Dress. London: Thames & Hudson. p. 88</ref> The belted worn linen chiton was the primary garment for men and women.<ref>Rief Anawalt, Patricia (2007): The Worldwide History of Dress. London: Thames & Hudson. p. 89</ref>

