In 1985 the French [[時尚設計|fashion designer]] [[让-保罗·高缇耶|Jean-Paul Gaultier]] created his first skirt for a men. Transgressing social codes Gaultier frequently introduces the skirt into his men's wear collections as a means of injecting novelty into male attire, most famously the sarong seen on [[大卫·贝克汉姆|David Beckham]].<ref>Fogg, Marnie (2011) ''The Fashion Design Directory''. London: Thames & Hudson. p. 165.</ref> Other famous designers such as [[薇薇安·魏斯伍德|Vivienne Westwood]], [[乔治·阿玛尼|Giorgio Armani]], [[约翰·加利亚诺|John Galliano]], [[高田贤三|Kenzo]], [[川久保玲|Rei Kawakubo]] and [[山本耀司|Yohji Yamamoto]] also created men's skirts.<ref>Fogg, Marnie (2011) ''The Fashion Design Directory''. London: Thames & Hudson. p. 316.</ref> In the US [[馬克·雅各布斯|Marc Jacobs]] became the most prominent supporter of the skirt for men. The Milan men's fashion shows and the New York fashion shows frequently show skirts for men. {{tsl|en|Jonathan Davis||Jonathan Davis}}, the lead singer of [[Korn|Korn]], has been known to wear kilts at live shows and in music videos throughout his 18-year career with that band. [[米克·贾格尔|Mick Jagger]] from the [[滚石乐队|Rolling Stones]] and [[安東尼·基德斯|Anthony Kiedis]] from the [[嗆辣紅椒|Red Hot Chili Peppers]] were photographed wearing dresses by [[安東·寇班|Anton Corbijn]].<ref>Corbijn, Anton (2000): Werk. Schirmer/ Mosel (Germany). p. 70</ref> For an {{tsl|en|FCKH8||FCKH8}} anti-discrimination campaign [[伊基·波普|Iggy Pop]] was seen wearing a black dress and handbag. [[枪与玫瑰|Guns N' Roses]]' singer, [[埃克索尔·罗斯|Axl Rose]], was known to wear men's skirts during the {{tsl|en|Use Your Illusion Tour||Use Your Illusion}} period. [[罗比·威廉斯|Robbie Williams]] and [[馬丁·戈爾|Martin Gore]] from [[流行尖端|Depeche Mode]] also performed on stage in skirts. During his Berlin time (1984–1985) Martin Gore was often seen in public wearing skirts. In an interview with the Pop Special Magazin (7/1985) he said: "Sexual barriers and gender roles are old fashioned and out. [...] I and my girlfriend often share our clothes and Make-up". Brand Nubian {{tsl|en|Lord Jamar||Lord Jamar}} criticized [[肯伊·威斯特|Kanye West]] wearing skirts, saying that his style has no place in hip-hop.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u8Wfw1QrAa8 |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211221/u8Wfw1QrAa8 |archive-date=2021-12-21 |url-status=live|title=Lord Jamar: Kanye's Skirt Has No Place in Hip-Hop|last=djvlad|date=1 February 2013|via=YouTube}}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TO8jHxrE4iI |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211221/TO8jHxrE4iI |archive-date=2021-12-21 |url-status=live|title=Kanye West Was Serious About His Skirt Kilt|last=JungleBookJokes|date=19 January 2013|via=YouTube}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

In 2008 in France, an association was created to help spur the revival of the skirt for men.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Frenchmen fighting for the right to wear skirts|work=[[衛報|The Guardian]]|date=2008-08-04|author=Lizzy Davies|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2008/aug/04/fashion.gender|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited | location=London}}</ref>
Hot weather has also encouraged use.  In June 2013, Swedish train drivers won the right to wear skirts in the summer when their cabins can reach {{convert|35|C|F}},<ref name=Arrivabeeb>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-22847008|title=Sweden's Arriva lifts shorts ban for skirt-wearing drivers|work=BBC news|date=10 June 2013|access-date=16 July 2013}}</ref> whilst in July 2013, parents supported boys wearing skirts at {{tsl|en|Gowerton Comprehensive School||Gowerton Comprehensive School}} in [[威爾斯|Wales]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/topics/weather/10179859/Swansea-schoolboys-keep-cool-in-skirts-after-shorts-ban.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130716081050/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/topics/weather/10179859/Swansea-schoolboys-keep-cool-in-skirts-after-shorts-ban.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=16 July 2013|title=Swansea schoolboys keep cool in skirts after shorts ban|work=Daily Telegraph|date=15 Jul 2013|access-date=16 July 2013}}</ref>

America is also not without its own contemporary advocates of skirts as menswear. One male blogger "denies that skirts are exclusively feminine garments" and suggests that the prevailing societal view reflects a "symbology of power" that persisted even in wake of the {{tsl|en|women's liberation movement||women's liberation movement}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voxclamantisindeserto.us/2016/11/why-i-wear-skirts/|title=Why I Wear Skirts|date=28 Nov 2016|access-date=3 Oct 2018}}</ref> He suggests an apparent causality paradox in the perception of skirts as exclusively womenswear: "are skirts perceived as feminine because women wear them or do women wear them because skirts are perceived as feminine?"<ref name="A Guy's Guide to Getting Skirted">{{cite web|url=http://www.voxclamantisindeserto.us/2018/02/a-guys-guide-to-getting-skirted/|title=A Guy's Guide to Getting Skirted|date=14 Feb 2018|access-date=3 Oct 2018}}</ref> Though lamenting the lack skirts designed specifically for men, he discusses in detail how to "advance a viewpoint of masculine aesthetics" in his how-to guide for men.<ref name="A Guy's Guide to Getting Skirted"/> Other internet denizens echo these sentiments  (with varying degrees of anonymity) in the "Skirt Cafe" internet forum "dedicated to exploring, promoting and advocating skirts and kilts as a fashion choice for men."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skirtcafe.org/forums/viewtopic.php?t=9620|work=Skirt Cafe|title=Introduction and Summary of the Rules|date=27 Aug 2007|access-date=3 Oct 2018}}</ref> However, the forum's moderators conspicuously assert that "this is NOT a transvestite or crossdresser forum. We are committed to a fundamentally masculine gender identity."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skirtcafe.org/forums/viewtopic.php?t=9620|title=Introduction and Summary of the Rules|work=Skirt Cafe|date=27 Aug 2007|access-date=3 Oct 2018}}</ref>

=== 大都會藝術博物館展覽 ===
In 2003, the [[大都會藝術博物館|Metropolitan Museum of Art]] displayed an exhibition, organized by {{tsl|en|Andrew Bolton (curator)||Andrew Bolton}} and {{tsl|en|Harold Koda||Harold Koda}} of the Museum's Costume Institute and sponsored by [[让-保罗·高缇耶|Gaultier]], entitled ''Bravehearts: Men in Skirts''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Bravehearts: Men in Skirts|author=Bolton, Andrew|year=2003|publisher=Harry N. Abrams|isbn=0-8109-6558-5}}</ref> The idea of the exhibition was to explore how various groups and individuals (from [[嬉皮士|hippie]]s through pop stars to fashion designers) have promoted the idea of men wearing skirts as "the future of menswear".  It displayed men's skirts on mannequins, as if in the window of a department store, in several historical and cross-cultural contexts.<ref name=Ellsworth>{{cite book|title=Places of Learning Media, Architecture, Pedagogy|url=https://archive.org/details/placeslearningme00ells_373|url-access=limited|author=Elizabeth Ann Ellsworth|pages=[https://archive.org/details/placeslearningme00ells_373/page/n153 143]–146|year=2005|publisher=Routledge|isbn=0-415-93158-4}}</ref>

The exhibition display pointed out the lack of a "natural link" between an item of clothing and the masculinity or femininity of the wearer, mentioning the [[蘇格蘭裙|kilt]] as "one of the most potent, versatile, and enduring skirt forms often looked upon by fashion designers as a symbol of a natural, uninhibited, masculinity".  It pointed out that fashion designers and male skirt-wearers employ the wearing of skirts for three purposes: to transgress conventional moral and social codes, to redefine the ideal of masculinity, and to inject novelty into male fashion.  It linked the wearing of men's skirts to youth movements and [[反文化|countercultural movement]]s such as [[朋克搖滾|punk]], [[油漬搖滾|grunge]], and [[華麗搖滾|glam rock]] and to pop-music icons such as [[佐治童子|Boy George]], [[MIYAVI|Miyavi]] and {{tsl|en|Adrian Young||Adrian Young}}.<ref name=Ellsworth /> Many male musicians have worn skirts and kilts both on and off stage. The wearing of skirts by men is also found in the [[哥德次文化|goth subculture]].

Elizabeth Ellsworth, a professor of [[媒體研究|media studies]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newschool.edu/public-engagement/faculty-list/?id=4d54-5934-4e7a-5131|title=Elizabeth Ellsworth - Professor of Media Studies - Public Engagement|website=www.newschool.edu}}</ref> eavesdropped on several visitors to the exhibition, noting that because of the exhibition's placement in a self-contained space accessed by a staircase at the far end of the museum's first floor, the visitors were primarily self-selected as those who would be intrigued enough by such an idea in the first place to actually seek it out.  According to her report, the reactions were wide-ranging, from the number of women who teased their male companions about whether they would ever consider wearing skirts (to which several men responded that they would) to the man who said, "A caftan after a shower or in the gym? Can you imagine? 'Excuse me!  Coming through!'".  An adolescent girl rejected in disgust the notion that skirts were similar to the wide pants worn by [[嘻哈|hip-hop]] artists. Two elderly women called the idea "utterly ridiculous".  One man, reading the exhibition's presentation on the subject of male skirt-wearing in cultures other than those in North America and Europe, observed, "God! Three quarters of the world's population [wear skirts]!"<ref name=Ellsworth />

The exhibition itself attempted to provoke visitors into considering how, historically, male-dress codes have come to this point and whether in fact a trend towards the wearing of skirts by men in the future actually exists.  It attempted to raise challenging questions of how a simple item of dress connotes (in Ellsworth's words) "huge ramifications in meanings, behaviours, everyday life, senses of self and others, and configurations of insider and outsider".<ref name=Ellsworth />

=== 現代風格 ===
The wearing of skirts, kilts, or similar garments on an everyday basis by men in Western cultures is an extremely small minority.{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}} One manufacturer of contemporary kilt styles claims to sell over 12,000 such garments annually,<ref>{{cite news |author=Staff |title=It's a cargo skirt – for guys. |date=September 19, 2005 |publisher=WTVG-TV News|place=[[托莱多_(俄亥俄州)|Toledo, Ohio]] }}</ref> resulting in over $2 million annually worth of sales, and has appeared at a major fashion show.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/business/301419_retail27.html|title=Manly skirt is not just for Scots anymore|author=Craig Harris|access-date=2007-05-18|work=[[西雅图邮讯报|Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] (online edition)|date=2007-01-26}}</ref> According to a [[有线电视新闻网|CNN]] correspondent: "At Seattle's Fremont Market, men are often seen sporting the {{tsl|en|Utilikilts||Utilikilt}}."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0101/07/sm.12.html |title=Tailor Revives Art of Kilt-Making |access-date=2007-05-18  |date=January 7, 2001 |work=Sunday Morning News |publisher=[[有线电视新闻网|CNN]] |quote=At Seattle's Fremont Market, men are often seen sporting the Utilikilt}}</ref> In 2003, ''US News'' said that "... the Seattle-made utilikilt, a rugged, everyday riff on traditional Scottish garb, has leapt from idea to over 10,000 sold in just three years, via the Web and word of mouth alone."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/usnews/culture/articles/030505/5tryitout.div.htm |title=Escaping the tyranny of trousers |access-date=2007-05-18 |work=U.S. News & World Report |date=May 5, 2003 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070317175825/http://www.usnews.com/usnews/culture/articles/030505/5tryitout.div.htm |archive-date=March 17, 2007 }}</ref> "They've become a common sight around Seattle, especially in funkier neighbourhoods and at the city's many alternative cultural events. They often are worn with chunky black boots," 