=== 威卡與新異教主義 ===
In [[威卡教|Wicca]] and [[新異教主義|neopaganism]], especially in the United States, men (just as women) are encouraged to question their traditional gender roles.  Amongst other things, this involves the wearing of robes at festivals and {{tsl|en|Sabbath (witchcraft)||sabbat}} celebrations as ritual clothing (which Eilers equates to the "church clothes" worn by Christians on Sundays).<ref>{{cite book|title=A Community of Witches: Contemporary Neo-paganism and Witchcraft in the United States|author=Helen A. Berger|pages=[https://archive.org/details/communityofwitch00berg/page/43 43]|year=1999|publisher=University of South Carolina Press|isbn=1-57003-246-7|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/communityofwitch00berg/page/43}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Practical Pagan: Common Sense Guidelines for Modern Practitioners|url=https://archive.org/details/practicalpaganco00eile|author=Dana D. Eilers|pages=[https://archive.org/details/practicalpaganco00eile/page/n153 153]|year=2002|publisher=Career Press|isbn=1-56414-601-4}}</ref>  Some [[教派|denomination]]s (called 'traditions') of Wicca even encourage their members to include [[长袍|robes]], [[丘尼卡|tunics]], [[斗篷|cloaks]], and other such garments in their day-to-day wardrobes.

